Here's a complete implementation:

```csharp
// In Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Configure max request body size (slightly above 10MB to allow for multipart overhead)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 11 * 1024 * 1024;
});

builder.Services.AddAntiforgery();

var app = builder.Build();

app.UseAntiforgery();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFile file) =>
{
    const long maxSize = 10 * 1024 * 1024; // 10MB

    if (file.Length == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No file provided.");

    if (file.Length > maxSize)
        return Results.BadRequest("File exceeds 10MB limit.");

    var allowedTypes = new[] { "image/jpeg", "image/png" };
    if (!allowedTypes.Contains(file.ContentType, StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
        return Results.BadRequest("Only JPEG and PNG files are allowed.");

    var uploadsPath = Path.Combine(app.Environment.ContentRootPath, "uploads");
    Directory.CreateDirectory(uploadsPath);

    // Use a random filename to prevent overwrites and path traversal
    var extension = file.ContentType == "image/png" ? ".png" : ".jpg";
    var fileName = $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{extension}";
    var filePath = Path.Combine(uploadsPath, fileName);

    await using var stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Create);
    await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

    return Results.Ok(new { fileName, size = file.Length });
})
.DisableAntiforgery(); // Remove this line if you want CSRF protection on this endpoint

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **Kestrel limit** — set slightly above 10MB to account for multipart boundaries; the explicit `file.Length` check enforces the real cap.
- **Content-type validation** — checks MIME type. For stricter validation, also inspect the file's magic bytes.
- **Safe filenames** — `Guid.NewGuid()` avoids path traversal and collisions.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — needed if clients (e.g., mobile apps) won't send an antiforgery token. Remove it to enforce CSRF protection for browser-based uploads (clients must then send the token via header/form field).

If you're behind IIS/reverse proxy, also add to `web.config`:

```xml
<system.webServer>
  <security>
    <requestFiltering>
      <requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength="11534336" />
    </requestFiltering>
  </security>
</system.webServer>
```
